WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.720
&gt;&gt; 
Today, we're lucky enough to have two authors

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.580
with us. They're both reporters at the Wall
Street Journal. Roger Thurow has been with

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:20.090
the journal as a foreign correspondent for
20 years and has reported on more than 60

00:00:20.090 --> 00:00:24.950
countries including two dozen in Africa. Scott
Kilman has been the journal's leading agricultural

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:29.710
reporter. Together, they have teamed up to
produce a stream of page one stories that

00:00:29.710 --> 00:00:34.640
have broken new ground in our understanding
of famine and food aid. Their stories on three

00:00:34.640 --> 00:00:41.339
2003 famines were a finalist for the 2004
Pulitzer Prize in international reporting.

00:00:41.339 --> 00:00:44.771
So please welcome them to discuss their book:
"Enough." Thank you.

00:00:44.771 --> 00:00:55.860
&gt;&gt; THUROW: Thank you and thanks for coming.
I'm Roger, this is Scott. Scott, Roger. I

00:00:55.860 --> 00:01:01.390
think our families know us as Roger, Scott,
Scott, Roger. They've become familiar with

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:08.780
us talking over the years. Thank you very
much for coming. This book, as Scott said,

00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:14.160
we both have been deeply involved in issues
of hunger and even culture development and,

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:19.830
and what is known as food security for much
of the past decade in our reporting. So, this

00:01:19.830 --> 00:01:25.250
book really encapsulates our passion about
the subjects, and figured if we didn't do

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:31.450
this book, our souls would never rest. And
so, I hope you, guys, all have copies and

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:39.410
that you enjoy it and learn something along
the way. Enough. Why enough? We have three

00:01:39.410 --> 00:01:45.730
meanings in this one little word. One, first,
there's enough food in the world to feed everybody

00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:51.550
which means the world is producing enough
food and has for the last number of decades,

00:01:51.550 --> 00:02:00.230
for everybody to have sufficient, nutritional
sustenance. The second, enough is enough.

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:05.921
We brought hunger with us into the 21st century
and shame on us for doing so. The Green Revolution

00:02:05.921 --> 00:02:10.470
was one of the great technological and scientific
achievements of the 20th century, and here

00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:15.680
we are nine years into 21st century, not only
have we brought hunger with us, but we brought

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:23.359
it with us in an increasing amount. This year,
the number of hungry in the world and severely

00:02:23.359 --> 00:02:30.060
malnourished is already soaring past one billion.
People, that's the highest level since before

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:34.040
the Green Revolution began in the 1960s and
the 1970s or when the Green Revolution kicked

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:42.129
in. And, for the first time since then, the
prevalence of hunger in the world is growing

00:02:42.129 --> 00:02:47.269
which means the percentage of hungry people
among the population and those are, those

00:02:47.269 --> 00:02:54.150
are just incredibly damning statistics that
for our age, you know, as you guys are all

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:59.370
intimately familiar with we've done so many
wonderful things, you know, wiring the world

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:03.529
for the Internet, Google and the marvelous
things you do but we still can't feed our

00:03:03.529 --> 00:03:11.169
fellow man and that problem is getting even
worse. Three--there's enough people. You guys

00:03:11.169 --> 00:03:21.859
that are gathered here, everybody involved
in the google.org; the process and efforts

00:03:21.859 --> 00:03:27.519
to get involved in development issues and
help the hungry and the poor of the world.

00:03:27.519 --> 00:03:33.019
And, you guys were all part of a bigger and
much larger movement, a Grassroots Movement

00:03:33.019 --> 00:03:38.799
that is a foot particularly on the hunger
issues that comes from churches and synagogues,

00:03:38.799 --> 00:03:48.150
and temples, and mosques, and university campuses,
small farms, big institutions from peasant

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:53.329
farmers in Africa to the leaders in Africa,
to CEOs and corporate headquarters in the

00:03:53.329 --> 00:03:57.419
United States and then Europe. And to some
of the great philanthropists of the world:

00:03:57.419 --> 00:04:03.209
Bill Gates, Warren Buffett; Howard Buffett,
Warren's son, who we'll see later, all intimately

00:04:03.209 --> 00:04:09.629
involved in the hunger issue and really, are
really giving it a great momentum. Our mantra

00:04:09.629 --> 00:04:13.889
in writing the book kind of constantly threw
the, I guess, it was through the report in

00:04:13.889 --> 00:04:18.650
that, it inspired us to do this and the stories
for the Wall Street Journal. But while writing

00:04:18.650 --> 00:04:25.080
the book, our mantra has been outrage and
inspire. We want, we want to outrage the readers

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:30.100
and also about that we brought hunger with
us into the 21st century, but also inspire

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:33.600
that we can actually do something about it,
and hunger is one of the great problems of

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:38.430
the world that can actually be conquered.
We have the tools, we have the intelligence,

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:44.510
we have the science to do it and it is something
that basically everybody can get involved

00:04:44.510 --> 00:04:52.450
with. And, our own personal outrage, I guess,
began to stir after 9/11. When we started,

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:59.120
I was overseas; Scott was in Chicago covering
agriculture, domestically and the impact around

00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:02.680
the world, and I was seeing things on the
ground in Africa. We started asking questions

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:09.390
about, well, what policies in the United States
and in Europe, government policies, the economic

00:05:09.390 --> 00:05:17.730
policies really impact in the fact and particularly
negatively impact people in the developing

00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:22.041
world, particularly the poor in the developing
world and in the most cases, they are farmers.

00:05:22.041 --> 00:05:25.780
And so we started asking, one of the central
questions we were asking is why can't Africa

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:30.751
feed itself, and why did Africa miss out in
the Green Revolution? And in our reporting,

00:05:30.751 --> 00:05:36.560
we came across something that Norman Borlaug
who is known as the father of the Green Revolution,

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:47.000
a very humble plant scientist from small town
Iowa and he won a Nobel Peace Prize in 1974,

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.960
his work on the Green Revolution. And, basically,
is known as perhaps the one human being who

00:05:54.960 --> 00:06:01.690
has saved more lives than anybody else. In
his Nobel Peace Prize speech, it was the lecture

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:06.650
of the day afterwards; he said something that's
very prophetic and incredibly haunting when

00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:11.520
you think about it in the context of the 21st
century. And he's saying this in 1970: "Man

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:16.170
can and must prevent the tragedy of famine
in the future instead of merely trying with

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:20.830
pious regret to salvage the human wreckage
of the famine as he has so often done in the

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:28.540
past. We will be guilty of criminal negligence
without extenuation if we permit future famines."

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:34.501
Criminal negligence. The light went off with
Scott and myself, that's what we are. We're

00:06:34.501 --> 00:06:38.870
basically criminal, we're basically crime
reporters because what were we doing as we

00:06:38.870 --> 00:06:44.770
were reporting about hunger is we were investigating
one of the great crimes of our, of our time;

00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:49.470
that was even five or six years ago, and now
if you bring it back or advance it, here we

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:54.130
are even further and the hunger situation
is getting worse. The crime continues, it's

00:06:54.130 --> 00:06:59.480
from, you know, our own neglect as Borlaug
said, "It's good intentions gone bad," and

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:05.520
we try to get on, into all of this in the
book. And then the Ethiopian famine of 2003

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:10.070
was another turning point for us and also
for the greater fight against hunger. That

00:07:10.070 --> 00:07:17.350
famine in 2003 in Ethiopia was worse than
the one in 1984; I don't know how old all

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:25.840
of your guys are. The famine of 1984 was a
milestone for, say people of our generation,

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:31.940
it was kind of one of the first global events,
the Live Aid concerts put together by Bob

00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:38.130
Geldof, Bono was part of that, all sorts of
the bands in Britain, Ireland, and the United

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:43.210
States with a huge global concert, sang "We
Are World, Do They Know It's Christmas," raised

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:49.130
a lot of money, a lot of awareness for the
famine in Ethiopia in 1984. All sorts of pious

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:54.410
statements as Borlaug had referred to, never
again, it shouldn't happen again, a million

00:07:54.410 --> 00:08:01.670
people died in that famine in Ethiopia. Well,
here we were in 2003, 19 years later, famine

00:08:01.670 --> 00:08:06.830
once again hit in Ethiopia and worse than
the one in 1984. Worse in the sense of more

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:12.580
people being on the doorstep of starvation.
In 1984, there were maybe 10 to 12 million

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:17.800
that were on the doorstep of starvation; more
people died, it was a communist government.

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:22.710
There wasn't--the relief efforts were already
there in the country but, about 10 to 12 million

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:29.180
on the verge of starvation and needed to be
fed. In 2003, it was more than 14 million

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:34.979
people, so there were actually more people
in 2003 that were on the doorstep of starvation.

00:08:34.979 --> 00:08:40.700
What happened? There in lies the tale of our
book. It was Borlaug's criminal neglect come

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:51.260
to life or come to death. And, we--as I said,
it becomes the core of our book and we will

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:57.050
now go on a brief journey back to the famine
of 2003, and again, remember the mantra outrage

00:08:57.050 --> 00:09:00.450
and inspire. The first part of what we're
going to show you is to outrage, it's also

00:09:00.450 --> 00:09:05.279
the first part of the book then we'll do--we'll
come to some of the inspiration that's when

00:09:05.279 --> 00:09:08.590
Scott will take over because he's the more
inspirational of us; I'm the one harboring

00:09:08.590 --> 00:09:15.810
all these outrage over the situation. If you
spend too much time with me, you'll think,

00:09:15.810 --> 00:09:20.490
you'll obviously know the same thing. So,
the scene of the crime as Borlaug says, here

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:25.940
we are. These are emergency feeding tents
in Boricha, Ethiopia up on the highlands.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:28.950
&gt;&gt; KILMAN: You took this picture...
&gt;&gt; THUROW: I was there, I took these pictures

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:37.640
and a number of these that are coming. Interest
in explaining of what happened. Obviously,

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:45.240
the kids are in horrible shape. The one on
the right, the left, in the white shirt--I'm

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:52.220
looking backwards, is--the one in the white
shirt is Hagiorso Katayma [ph]. He was five

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:55.770
years old at that time and was brought in
by his father who's sitting behind him, he

00:09:55.770 --> 00:10:02.180
weighed only 27 pounds at five years old,
showing all the signs of, of horrible severe

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:08.920
malnutrition, the swollen stomach, the swollen
limbs and the swollen head from the various

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:14.710
manifestations of malnutrition from lack of
protein. And as you can see, he and the boy

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:19.920
next to him or the child next to him, that's
a boy or girl are being held up by their fathers,

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:23.060
they're propped between the legs, their fathers
have their hands on them because they're so

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:28.400
weak, they can't even, they can't even sit
up. The interesting thing is that their parents,

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:33.530
the men behind them are peasant farmers in
Ethiopia. They each have maybe, you know,

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:42.029
one or two acres of land. The year before,
they were carrying to the same market village

00:10:42.029 --> 00:10:48.450
in Ethiopia, bags of their surplus grain.
They had had their best harvest ever in the,

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:56.630
the 2001 harvest season and 2002, and at that
stage--and it was all across the country,

00:10:56.630 --> 00:11:05.370
it wasn't only these guys, but it was Ethiopia
had had its biggest harvest in history because

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:10.130
since 1984 famine, the push had been on in
Ethiopia and elsewhere in Africa to produce,

00:11:10.130 --> 00:11:17.839
produce, produce, to ramp up and increase
the production of grains as quickly and as

00:11:17.839 --> 00:11:24.540
mightily as possible. That they did and they
had great success. So these guys in 2001-2002

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:28.740
are carrying this huge hundred, hundred pound
bags of surplus grain to the market, they're

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:34.250
overjoyed. They finally have surplus crops,
a great income for the family. Well, what

00:11:34.250 --> 00:11:40.180
happened? They came to the market and because
of the surplus that the whole country had,

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:48.320
the prices collapsed by 80% across Ethiopia.
These guys ended up losing--the price that

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:51.940
they got was less than their cost of production,
less than the cost of the fertilizer, less

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:58.630
than the cost of the calculated cost of their
labor of the wagon that they had to use and

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:04.811
things and so, these guys lost money; they
reacted like farmers anywhere else. In the

00:12:04.811 --> 00:12:09.100
United States, we're from Illinois. We went
to the University of Iowa. We grew up surrounded

00:12:09.100 --> 00:12:13.970
in the cornfields and the wheat fields in
the Midwest. The farmers lose money, they

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:20.021
changed their tactics. They'll plant different
crops, they'll use cheaper inputs. These guys,

00:12:20.021 --> 00:12:24.510
the next year, what do they do? They cut back
on their use of fertilizer. Fertilizer use

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:33.279
in Ethiopia fell 27% the next year; this is
planting season for 2002-2003. They stopped

00:12:33.279 --> 00:12:38.980
using the better hybrid seeds; they took whatever
seeds they had in the back of their huts.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:43.861
They knew they were going to get, they weren't
as good as seeds. The use of hybrid seeds

00:12:43.861 --> 00:12:48.300
in Ethiopia fell 70%. That year as farmers
tried to cut production, some of the bigger

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:55.230
farmers took thousands of acres out of production.
They shut off their irrigation systems because

00:12:55.230 --> 00:13:00.610
they were too expensive that they couldn't
afford. And, they all knew they were going

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:06.630
to get less production because they were using
less fertilizer, not as good as seeds, but

00:13:06.630 --> 00:13:11.540
the calculation that these gentlemen made
was, that's okay, because we had a surplus

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:15.640
production. What did it do? We actually lost
money on it. We'll cut back our expenses.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:19.339
Okay, we'll grow less food but as long as
we have enough food to feed our families,

00:13:19.339 --> 00:13:27.180
that's great. That's our goal as peasant farmers,
that'll be great. What happened? Drought hit

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:32.490
the country which it does on a regular basis.
Everybody looked to the heavens for rain,

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:39.350
rain wasn't coming; it was very sporadic.
That impacted their crops, the production

00:13:39.350 --> 00:13:44.790
which they thought would be lower, fell even
more. Hunger spread across the country, tips

00:13:44.790 --> 00:13:50.920
in the famine across the country. These two
gentlemen, Tasfia [ph], the man in the brown

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:57.750
shirt behind his son Hagiorso [ph], they are
carrying their children to the market where

00:13:57.750 --> 00:14:03.890
the year before they had carried their huge
surplus grains of wheat. In their success

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:10.560
came their failure, from feast came famine.
The whole of economics of farming for these

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:19.160
guys stood on their heads. It's a horrible
and cruel paradox that during the boost to

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:23.810
push production in Ethiopia and elsewhere
in Africa but, particularly, in Ethiopia,

00:14:23.810 --> 00:14:30.330
the markets were ignored. The markets failed
before the weather did. And so the lesson

00:14:30.330 --> 00:14:36.029
of all this is markets matter. Here are some
other people in that same, that same feeding

00:14:36.029 --> 00:14:41.459
tent, and again, out of their success came
failure, feast led the famine; one of the

00:14:41.459 --> 00:14:49.810
cruelest ironies that one can see in Africa.
Wow. What's this? Also in Ethiopia, not far

00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:54.231
from the emergency feeding tents maybe a couple
of hours drive. This is an Ethiopian farmer

00:14:54.231 --> 00:14:58.580
and grain trader. He's standing in the warehouse
and this is, this is what is stacked up in

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:07.110
front of him are stacks of corn, wheat, beans,
peas, lentils that had come from the surplus

00:15:07.110 --> 00:15:13.800
of the two previous harvest. Why is this here?
Because these guys had some warehouse facilities,

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:19.050
they figured if they store it, it'll help
support prices a little bit. If all of this

00:15:19.050 --> 00:15:22.410
grain that they had stored in these warehouses
went on the market, the prices instead of

00:15:22.410 --> 00:15:27.430
collapsing 80%, you know, would've gone down
even further or would have taken such a long

00:15:27.430 --> 00:15:36.589
time to recover, so these guys held it in
the warehouses. There's another picture. Where

00:15:36.589 --> 00:15:43.021
these guys are is in the town of Nazareth,
in a little bit east of the capital of Addis

00:15:43.021 --> 00:15:52.279
Ababa. Two blocks away is where the road from
Djibouti where is the nearest port runs to

00:15:52.279 --> 00:15:56.870
the capital of Addis, that's the same road
where all the Food Aid that comes, that were

00:15:56.870 --> 00:16:00.760
streaming in the country to feed this 14 million
people that were hungry. The bulk of the Food

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:07.420
Aid or at least over 50% of the Food Aid that
year was coming from the United States. So

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:11.930
here comes all these grain and corn and wheat
and soybeans and all of this Food Aid from

00:16:11.930 --> 00:16:17.480
the United States running pass these warehouses
in Ethiopia, they're full of grain. Again,

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:22.760
all the way up to the ceiling, a staggering
sight in a country that is experiencing famine.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:27.860
Why was this happening? Because of the US
Food Aid policy. It's mandated in the US that

00:16:27.860 --> 00:16:34.560
we have to ship American grown food for Food
Aid around the world. We can't use cash from

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:40.110
the federal government budget to buy this
food that's already sitting there and would

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:43.700
be a huge incentive and a huge market for
the farmers of Ethiopia and elsewhere in Africa

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:46.830
if somebody would come in, particularly, the
United States and buy their grain in a time

00:16:46.830 --> 00:16:54.200
of, in a time of famine. So if you stood outside
the warehouses and stood inside in their parking

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:58.760
lots, you could literally feel the rumble
of the trucks laden with the big, huge double

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:03.100
wide trucks laden with Food Aid from the United
States rumbling pass their warehouses full

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:08.150
of Ethiopian food to basically feed the starving
Ethiopians and these guys are wondering, well,

00:17:08.150 --> 00:17:13.760
how come, they're not sending our food or
using our food? This guy, German Mamente [ph]

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:17.549
he climbed to the--climbed to the top of his,
one of stack, he said, "Roger, take my picture

00:17:17.549 --> 00:17:22.230
and put this picture on the Wall Street Journal
with the caption, 'Please send food, Ethiopians

00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:28.520
are starving, we have no food in Ethiopia.'"
It's terribly ironic. He laughed hilariously

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:38.770
at that in a fit of gallous humor; that basically
encapsulates one of the, another of the horrible

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:44.929
ironies. These guys then got together, a number
of the commercial farmers and traders and

00:17:44.929 --> 00:17:49.710
they wrote a letter to their government. The
Food Aid coming to the country is great, saving

00:17:49.710 --> 00:17:55.350
a lot of people, our fellow Ethiopians, but
first can you tell the donors and the government

00:17:55.350 --> 00:18:00.809
in sending the Food Aid, "Please buy our grain
first because if we don't sell our grain;

00:18:00.809 --> 00:18:04.230
one, we're not going to have room to store
it next year and two, we're not going to have

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:09.650
any money to buy the, the crops to the farmers
in this planting season, in this, in the following

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:13.090
places." We're going to end up in the same
situation. There is going to be another, there

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:15.960
is going to be another lack of food, prices
are going to collapse, the farmers are going

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:21.170
to lose all incentive again to grow. At the
same time, in the United States, so I'm in

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:25.460
Ethiopia talking with these guys about this,
Scott's talking to farmers in the United States

00:18:25.460 --> 00:18:29.890
and, and the folks in the White House. A group
of American farmers at the same time, led

00:18:29.890 --> 00:18:33.871
by the Wheat Association was writing a letter
to the White House--it's Clinton White House

00:18:33.871 --> 00:18:36.550
right, on 2003, no?
&gt;&gt; KILMAN: Bush.

00:18:36.550 --> 00:18:45.490
&gt;&gt; THUROW: Bush. Bush's White House, saying
please include more American food and particularly

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:50.170
American--in American Food Aid shipments because
we've had a surplus and a great harvest in

00:18:50.170 --> 00:18:54.020
the United States and there's pressure on
our wheat prices in the United States. "Please

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:59.840
send the food overseas in Food Aid." The conclusion
on the Ethiopians and it's hard to dispute

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:07.520
with them is American farmers need starving
Ethiopians; two letters, two sets of farmers,

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:16.770
exact opposite purposes at the same time in
the midst of a famine. These two guys, lentil

00:19:16.770 --> 00:19:25.980
farmers in Ethiopia, they are standing--they're
in all their sartorial splendor, and typical

00:19:25.980 --> 00:19:30.950
dress, they're wearing rags--this stuff is
all kind of put together. Scott will talk

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:35.050
about this later, most of the farmers in Africa
and, and in the developing world and particularly

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:42.020
in Africa, are women. It's just coincidental
that some of these photos are men. These guys

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:46.299
were on the road, the same Djibouti to Addis
road where the Food Aid trucks are running

00:19:46.299 --> 00:19:51.760
pass. I'm talking to them, a huge convoy of
Food Aid trucks go by and there's a little

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:56.551
bit of cargo that basically drips out of the
trucks and kind of scatters along the road.

00:19:56.551 --> 00:20:00.361
The trucks go pass; we all run into the road,
these guys are particularly curious "What

00:20:00.361 --> 00:20:04.700
is this, what feel out?" Again, I said these
guys are lentil farmers, they bend over and

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:08.660
they picked it up and it's lentils and they
said "Where is this coming from?" and I said

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:12.750
"Well, based on the markings of the trucks,
on the bags, on the trucks, I think it's coming

00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:18.570
from the United States" and they said "Well,
why are they sending lentils to America, or

00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:21.740
why are they sending lentils to Ethiopia?
Don't they know in America that we grow lentils

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:26.051
in Ethiopia?" I said "No, I don't think they
know in America that you grow lentils in Ethiopia

00:20:26.051 --> 00:20:31.460
and that you should grow a surplus of lentils
that they can export some." And so, again

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:37.570
setting up the huge irony and contradiction
that it's almost, you know coals to New Castle

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:42.790
in the midst of a famine and Ethiopia had
food from its previous shares of surplus production

00:20:42.790 --> 00:20:50.120
we're sending in that. What this also represents
is the neglect that Borlaug talked about,

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:55.960
a huge part of that was the huge fall off
in development aid for agriculture and agriculture

00:20:55.960 --> 00:21:02.980
development, and particularly in Africa. And
in Ethiopia, and it was not only by the United

00:21:02.980 --> 00:21:09.510
States but by all the western countries and
the rich governments of the world. In Ethiopia

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:17.929
in 2003 and it's a stunning set of numbers.
There was $500 million in this American Food

00:21:17.929 --> 00:21:22.650
Aid that was coming to Ethiopia that year,
$500 million in food from America that was

00:21:22.650 --> 00:21:28.780
coming to Ethiopia. That same year in 2003,
U.S. agriculture development aid to Ethiopia

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:34.970
was less than $5 million. Less than $5 million
to help them grow food so that they wouldn't

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:42.500
be hungry to begin with; $500 million in food
to say "That's okay, we'll feed you." Again,

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:46.220
a damning statistics, why are we doing that?
What's wrong with our policies? Why aren't

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:49.970
we helping the Ethiopians to grow as much
food as possible and to feed themselves as

00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:57.919
opposed to us sending our food to feed them
when they do become hungry? This man with

00:21:57.919 --> 00:22:04.040
the scarf in his head, on a turban, it was
a very hot day, it was cooling him off is

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:09.990
Tasfahum Valijud [ph], Tasfahum [ph] means
"be hope" in the Amharic language. When I

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:18.090
saw him in the midst of--this is in 2003 again.
Mr. "Be Hope" had basically lost all hope.

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:22.160
He's standing beside the Red River which is
one of the tributaries of the Blue Nile. The

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:31.620
Blue Nile is one of the great waterways of
Africa. It gathers steam and a tremendous

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:37.260
power runs over gorges and cascades and basically
500 miles that it runs through Ethiopia and

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:41.730
the Sudan, Sudan connects the White Nile which
is coming up from the great lakes region of

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:46.929
Central Africa and together they form in Sudan--in
Khartoum in Sudan and then they form the great

00:22:46.929 --> 00:22:52.700
Nile which runs through, up through Egypt.
Tasfahum at this stage, he's got the water

00:22:52.700 --> 00:22:57.040
running right pass him. His farm, his little
plot of an acre or two which is right to the

00:22:57.040 --> 00:23:01.260
side of the picture, is bone dry. There's
nothing growing because of the drought, whatever

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:06.230
he had planted has died. He's been on Food
Aid for nine months at this time. Well, the

00:23:06.230 --> 00:23:11.940
Food Aid from America is streaming into the
country, and I asked him "Well, why aren't

00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:16.429
you taking the water from the Red River running
in front of you right by your feet and irrigating

00:23:16.429 --> 00:23:20.100
your land?" and he said "You know, well, we
thought about that." You know, he kind of

00:23:20.100 --> 00:23:24.760
fixes me with a gaze, you know, we're not
dumb, we thought about that. We have tried

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:29.510
to do that; the government basically comes
by and says "You can't do that." Why? The

00:23:29.510 --> 00:23:35.440
water belongs in Egypt. What happened was,
is that Ethiopia had the great fortune of

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:40.500
never being colonized by a European power--one
of the rare African countries for that to

00:23:40.500 --> 00:23:46.150
happen. Ethiopia also had the great misfortune
of not being colonized by a great European

00:23:46.150 --> 00:23:49.280
power because when the European powers came
together and the councils of Europe and said

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:54.440
"Well, what should we do about Africa?" They
then divvied up water rights and the Brits

00:23:54.440 --> 00:23:59.910
were in charge of--were the colonial powers
in Egypt and Sudan at that time and they said,

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:06.059
"Water of Egypt or the water of the Nile must
be for our cotton plantations and the granaries

00:24:06.059 --> 00:24:12.690
in Sudan and the granaries in Egypt. The downstream
users, we should have the right of the Nile

00:24:12.690 --> 00:24:18.030
water usage." There's nobody in Ethiopia to
stand up and say "Well, what about us?" Eighty-five

00:24:18.030 --> 00:24:22.900
percent of the water that runs through Egypt
and basically brings 8 million acres of land

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:29.470
in Egypt and of the Sahara Desert to bloom
and to produce a whole cornucopia of food,

00:24:29.470 --> 00:24:34.610
eighty-five percent of the water in Egypt,
in the Nile and in the canals comes from Ethiopia

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:41.000
and from the highlands of Ethiopia where they
usually get pretty good rain. It runs to the

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:46.370
Blue Nile or through some of the tributaries
that run into Sudan or in the canyon connect

00:24:46.370 --> 00:24:55.110
with the White Nile or the great Nile and
itself. And, so 85% of the water of the Nile

00:24:55.110 --> 00:25:02.120
which is irrigating 8 million acres back in
2003, in Ethiopia, less than 500,000 acres

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:08.290
are irrigated. So all the Ethiopian water
is being taken, is being irrigated and irrigating

00:25:08.290 --> 00:25:14.200
crops somewhere else and producing food elsewhere
and not here. And one of the great cruel ironies

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:22.230
is, is that the land that feeds the Nile can't
feed itself, and it was a screwed up system

00:25:22.230 --> 00:25:30.360
of geopolitics that allowed that to happen.
Now, this is an Egyptian farmer. He's 100

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:36.679
miles from the Nile. He's way out in the desert.
He's at the last stop in the desert that still

00:25:36.679 --> 00:25:41.799
gets Nile water. If he wants to expand his
farm, he's got to expand the canal system.

00:25:41.799 --> 00:25:49.200
This guy, I think he had 60 acres of a whole
array of peppers and lettuce and cucumbers

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:56.080
and tomatoes that were grown in hothouses.
Some grow corn, and wheat grown in his fields

00:25:56.080 --> 00:26:01.930
and he had a lot of cattle, these are water
buffalo calves, they're being showered. He

00:26:01.930 --> 00:26:07.230
says "Well, happy cattle are fatter cattle."
He sells them for a higher price. The water

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:15.940
that is showering them is Ethiopian water.
This guy is Food Aid. They can't grow, that's

00:26:15.940 --> 00:26:24.730
their water, runs into Nile. This man using
the water that perhaps is running by this

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:36.750
guy's feet, Tasfahum [ph] feet water his cattle.
Again, outrage. This is 2002, now we're in

00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:45.180
Mali in West Africa, subsidies issue of the
American farm subsidies. These guys are West

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:50.260
African cotton farmers. They are, you know,
dressed in rags. They do all their planting

00:26:50.260 --> 00:26:58.429
by hand. They are walking behind their two
draft oxen; they're not mechanized, whatsoever.

00:26:58.429 --> 00:27:05.910
I got to remember, this is an American cotton
farm in Mississippi. Now these two pictures

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:12.250
were taken on the same day. I was in Mali,
Scott was in the Mississippi Delta and it's

00:27:12.250 --> 00:27:17.710
the same day. These guys, the water, the rain
just started to fall, they figuring, "Well,

00:27:17.710 --> 00:27:22.940
the rain is coming, time to go prepare for
the planting season." I think they were doing

00:27:22.940 --> 00:27:28.960
the same in Mississippi on that day. This
is Ken Hood. He was the head of the American

00:27:28.960 --> 00:27:35.990
Cotton Counsel and Cotton Association, whatever
it's called. In 2002, was the Farm Bill that

00:27:35.990 --> 00:27:41.900
President Bush signed, and again, he signed
it five, six, seven months after 9/11 where

00:27:41.900 --> 00:27:46.330
President Bush was asking the question that
he said was on the minds of a whole bunch

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:50.970
of Americans at the time, and rightfully so,
why do they hate us so much? So they started

00:27:50.970 --> 00:27:55.881
the whole round of World Trade talks called
the Development Round. How do we make the

00:27:55.881 --> 00:28:02.460
World Trade benefit people in the developing
world? They have the Monterey Conference in

00:28:02.460 --> 00:28:06.260
Monterey, Mexico where everybody pledged,
we're going to increase our development aid

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:13.179
to the developing world. That, I think, was
in Doha, it was in November of 2001, Monterey

00:28:13.179 --> 00:28:21.330
in March or April of 2002. In May of 2002
comes U.S. Farm Bill which Bush signs, raising

00:28:21.330 --> 00:28:25.190
subsidies for American farmers and particularly
for American cotton farmers. The first person,

00:28:25.190 --> 00:28:30.480
President Bush turns around to shakes hands
with after signing the bill is Mr. Ken Hood

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:37.270
because and he has a big smile on his face
because his subsidies were greatly increased

00:28:37.270 --> 00:28:45.300
and the farmers are the potential subsidies
that they could get. No subsidies for these

00:28:45.300 --> 00:28:52.950
farmers in Mali and the government at the
same time was telling them that their price

00:28:52.950 --> 00:28:58.850
for their cotton is going to be cut by 5,
10, 15% that year because there was a glut

00:28:58.850 --> 00:29:05.510
of cotton in the world market. The world market,
the, all the cotton that basically is grown

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:09.080
in the United States, we don't have a cotton
industry anymore, we don't make t-shirts or

00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:16.470
underwear, and it drives down the prices.
The Mali government was able to pay less to

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:20.190
its own cotton farmers. So, if you look at
these two people and you'd wonder, "Wow, who

00:29:20.190 --> 00:29:22.799
should get the--who should get the aid from
the government, who should get the subsidies?"

00:29:22.799 --> 00:29:32.049
This guy should--does he need subsidies? That's
the question that we address in the book;

00:29:32.049 --> 00:29:35.180
that's the outrage section--inspiration Dr.
Borlaug?

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:39.330
&gt;&gt; KILMAN: Well, now they're all bummed out.
&gt;&gt; THUROW: Now they're all bummed out. You're

00:29:39.330 --> 00:29:43.560
thinking, what's going on? So, people should
be simply outraged as it is promises the world,

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:46.990
that's driving the hunger problem.
&gt;&gt; KILMAN: Roger has talked about the Green

00:29:46.990 --> 00:29:53.830
Revolution and this is all before your time.
Most of, most, everybody's in the wrong time.

00:29:53.830 --> 00:30:00.910
But, with the Green Revolution was in the
1960s and 1970s, hunger and famine was a problem

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:10.809
mostly of Asia, that's where the epicenter
was India and Pakistan. And this man had been--lucky

00:30:10.809 --> 00:30:17.340
coincidence, had been working in Mexico trying
to develop better types of wheat for the poor

00:30:17.340 --> 00:30:22.420
farmers of Mexico. And, what was happening
was that the farmers of Mexico would grow

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:29.530
their crop and would be wiped out by diseases.
So, he was given the job of trying to find

00:30:29.530 --> 00:30:37.030
wheat plants that could resist this disease
and he was successful. He was just a--I won't

00:30:37.030 --> 00:30:44.860
call him a simple scientist but he was--he
didn't start of thinking of himself as a humanitarian.

00:30:44.860 --> 00:30:52.539
He was given a scientific problem and he pursued
it, try to figure out how to solve it and

00:30:52.539 --> 00:30:57.870
he did. As it happened the way that he solved
it was he came up with a new way of breeding

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:04.370
wheat plants. Mexico is unique because there's
actually two places in Mexico where you can

00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:08.710
go grow wheat at different times of the year.
You can grow wheat continuously in Mexico

00:31:08.710 --> 00:31:13.980
just but in different parts. So he had to
figure out, you know, how do I, how do I stay

00:31:13.980 --> 00:31:17.929
ahead over this disease that keeps evolving
and keeps changing. Every time I come up with

00:31:17.929 --> 00:31:23.720
a new wheat plant, you know, this fungus evolves
quickly and it will destroy the wheat plant,

00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:28.010
so he had to speed up planting, he has to
speed up breeding and he did by breeding,

00:31:28.010 --> 00:31:32.890
by figuring out that he could breed two cycles.
In Mexico, you could actually two wheat crops

00:31:32.890 --> 00:31:37.211
in Mexico in a year but that meant traveling
more than a thousand miles back and forth

00:31:37.211 --> 00:31:42.340
on trucks. You need to harvest at one place,
take the seed, travel up to Northwest Mexico,

00:31:42.340 --> 00:31:47.350
plant it there, see how well it did, pick
the best ones, bring it down to around Mexico

00:31:47.350 --> 00:31:52.850
cities, so he speed up the breeding process.
In the process of doing that, he came up with

00:31:52.850 --> 00:31:56.570
a type of wheat plant nobody expected. It
was a type of wheat plant that could grow

00:31:56.570 --> 00:32:03.120
anywhere in the world. Most plants are very
sensitive to their environment, only grow

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:08.790
in a very unique place because the length
of daylight, the climate and the soil. But,

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:12.940
unintentionally, he came up with a super right--a
super wheat plant that would grow anywhere.

00:32:12.940 --> 00:32:20.520
So, when the India and Pakistan were having
their famines, he was the guy who had the

00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:26.730
seeds to plant a crop that could grow in India
and Pakistan and it worked, and the wheat

00:32:26.730 --> 00:32:33.150
production soared in India and Pakistan so
that by, you know, the 1960s--I have to look

00:32:33.150 --> 00:32:38.370
at the book but I think, in the late 1960s,
20% of all the wheat that was grown in the

00:32:38.370 --> 00:32:45.679
United States was being shipped to India for
Food Aid, 20%, one in five bushels. By the

00:32:45.679 --> 00:32:52.900
mid 1970s, India could feed itself. And, by
the late 1970s, India actually had excess

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:59.400
stock piles and in the '80s or '90s or some
years where India was actually exporting wheat.

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:04.940
People still think of India, and there's still
a lot of poverty, still a lot of hunger in

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:09.409
India but there weren't famines anymore. And
it was, it happened just because he was a

00:33:09.409 --> 00:33:15.961
stubborn guy, and he was given a very specific,
scientific problem and he solved it and a

00:33:15.961 --> 00:33:21.390
coincidence, he had the tool that could help
India and Pakistan; on a footnote, this is

00:33:21.390 --> 00:33:25.650
Norman Borlaug. He won the Nobel Peace Prize
in 1970 because of this, he was coined the

00:33:25.650 --> 00:33:33.080
Green Revolution. What happened, what he was
able to do to stop the famines in India and

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:38.970
Pakistan in the 1960s or 1970s, the seeds
spread throughout Asia, throughout Latin America

00:33:38.970 --> 00:33:49.159
and it was an amazing time in the '70s and
the '80s--something very unusual happened.

00:33:49.159 --> 00:33:55.429
If you put it in an economic function--what
happens is that the per capital availability

00:33:55.429 --> 00:34:01.539
of grain around the world actually grew which
nobody expected. Everybody thought that population,

00:34:01.539 --> 00:34:06.950
as Malthis said population grows faster than
food production, and he had more to do with

00:34:06.950 --> 00:34:11.569
anybody else to shovel that. We don't have
to be doomed to buy that idea. You can actually

00:34:11.569 --> 00:34:19.090
make more food available to everybody even
as the population is growing. But, it's interesting

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:23.300
because he's probably the most obscure Nobel
Peace Prize winner you'll never hear about.

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:34.790
He never made a lot of money, never patented
any of his inventions,

00:34:34.790 --> 00:34:39.500
and if he had, his techniques are not used
by a lot of SIG companies, biotechnology companies,

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:48.389
he'd be a very wealthy man but he lives in
a two-bedroom house in Dallas and lives very

00:34:48.389 --> 00:34:54.169
humbly. He's now 95 years old. I was just
with him a couple of weeks ago doing a video

00:34:54.169 --> 00:35:01.820
for the wsj.com, that will hopefully run this
weekend. And, here's this guy--what fascinated

00:35:01.820 --> 00:35:07.720
me about him was that, when you write a book
about hunger, it's a pretty daunting task

00:35:07.720 --> 00:35:11.530
because you start off and you think, well,
there are a million problems, it's an unsolvable

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:16.600
problem, there are a million problems. How
can--you know, how could you find any kind

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:22.210
of hope in this problem? And you look at Norman
Borlaug and you realize well, one person can

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:27.230
make a difference. He didn't intend to make
a difference but just doing his job and doing

00:35:27.230 --> 00:35:33.349
his work, he came across something was pretty
miraculous and he made a difference, what's

00:35:33.349 --> 00:35:36.460
the next [INDISTINCT]. Some of my notes in
the--so I'm to supposedly be the inspirational

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:41.260
one, a part of what we're talking. So, the
first half of the book basically lays out

00:35:41.260 --> 00:35:45.230
the problem. It makes the argument that hunger
is a solvable problem and the second part

00:35:45.230 --> 00:35:50.360
of the book focuses on people who are actually
doing something about it. So, Norman Borlaug

00:35:50.360 --> 00:35:55.500
is sort of the grand example of somebody who
can make a difference; who can still inspire

00:35:55.500 --> 00:36:04.010
people. One of the people who's doing, working
now in Africa is Howard Buffett. His last

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:09.060
name is a lot better known. He's the son of
Warren Buffet, the eldest son of Warren Buffet.

00:36:09.060 --> 00:36:18.770
He's one of the wealthiest men in the world.
You know, while Warren is an expert stack

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:23.750
picker and loves to sit in an office, he sits
in an office and goes through the financial

00:36:23.750 --> 00:36:29.750
data. Howard didn't want that kind of life;
he wanted to be a farmer, he like grew up

00:36:29.750 --> 00:36:37.180
in Omaha. He--as it turned out, you know,
in his farming life, he got more involved

00:36:37.180 --> 00:36:44.030
in political issues and agricultural issues,
and ended up working for some corporations.

00:36:44.030 --> 00:36:50.480
Archer Daniels Midland, he was on the board
of Kanegra, and the Coca-cola Enterprises,

00:36:50.480 --> 00:36:59.770
other companies like this. On one of his business
trips to Africa--go backward--no, no. On one

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:04.420
of his business trips to Africa, he took a
camera with him, and he is sort of conservationist.

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:08.210
He was very interested in the environment.
So, when he went Africa on a business trip,

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:12.000
he was interested in cheetahs, and you know,
gorillas, and saving the gorilla which is

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:20.640
all good stuff, and he had somebody supporting
that kind of thing. But it was in 2000, he

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:28.240
went to Northern Ghana to a town called Tamale,
you've been there, right? I've been there.

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:34.450
In Northern Ghana, and he was being--I think
he was accompanied by World Vision, one of

00:37:34.450 --> 00:37:38.500
the NGOs there, just trying to show him, you
know, different issues he should get involved

00:37:38.500 --> 00:37:45.460
with. He's walking through a hospital and
he sees this girl laying in a bed. And he--she's,

00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:52.099
basically, she's starving to death. She has
meningitis and she had something, she's malnourished

00:37:52.099 --> 00:37:53.530
but...
&gt;&gt; THUROW: Malaria.

00:37:53.530 --> 00:38:00.180
&gt;&gt; KILMAN: Meningitis and malaria. Her body
couldn't fight off diseases, and she dies

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:06.790
a few days after this picture was taken. And
this picture changed his life. He took this

00:38:06.790 --> 00:38:11.040
picture, it's really--it's in our book, it's
interesting to me because she's looking right

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:16.760
at him through the viewfinder. And he's a
father of five, and he sees this, and he told

00:38:16.760 --> 00:38:21.560
me--one of the first times I had to set down
my camera, I couldn't take any more pictures.

00:38:21.560 --> 00:38:26.830
And he ended up talking to the mother through
a translator, and something happened, he sort

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:32.190
of having--he started an epiphany that he
realized that the issue that he'd been concerned

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:37.650
